## F5 — LOW (Leg 3 note) — conservative stop rounding shrinks InitialRisk one-directionally

`_round_stop_conservative` always tightens (long=ceil toward entry, short=floor
toward entry), so InitialRisk is always rounded DOWN by up to one tick (0.25 pt).
Since `RealizedR = pnl_points / InitialRisk`, this inflates |R| (winners AND
losers) by up to ~1–2% of risk. The README rationale ("keeps stops no farther
from entry than the raw modeled stop") addresses fill realism but is silent on the
R-denominator effect, which is one-directional. Magnitude is sub-tick so headline
impact is negligible (and net-of-sign ambiguous), but the doc should acknowledge
the bias rather than imply rounding is neutral. Not a blocker.

