# Second-Audit Findings + Proposed Fixes (2026-05-23) — AWAITING CODEX AGREEMENT

A second audit pass surfaced eight items. I re-verified each against the real
data. NONE are active bugs (no current output changes), but several are worth
hardening. Each item below has a PROPOSED FIX and an explicit question for Codex.
Codex: for each, reply in your codexArg with AGREE / DISAGREE / COUNTER, and your
reasoning. Do not implement until we converge.

## S1 — 5 research columns are not session-grouped (consistency, NOT a data bug)

`SignalVolRatio`, `SignalVolRobustZ`, `SignalATRPctile`, `SignalVPIN`,
`SignalKyleLambdaPctile` are computed ungrouped across sessions. They DO produce
contaminated values on early-session bars — BUT I verified (recomputing grouped
vs ungrouped on the real discovery data) that they are byte-identical at every
signal-eligible bar (cumcount >= 19): max |diff| = 0.0, and zero signal bars where
ungrouped has a value and grouped would be NaN. Reason: these use `rolling(20)`
(mean/median/percentile), whose window ENDING at cumcount 19 spans cumcount 0..19
= in-session. This is the key difference from F1's `efficiency_ratio`, which used
`diff(20)` and so reached cumcount -1 AT the signal bar. So session-grouping these
changes zero joined values — it is a uniformity/defensive change, not a correction.

Proposed fix: session-group all 5 (groupby(session).transform / per-session loop)
so the whole research module is uniformly session-isolated, AND add the single
parametrized "every RESEARCH_INDICATOR_COLUMN resets at session boundary" test
(from the design-opinion section above) which would then cover them. Alternative:
keep ungrouped but add an explicit allowlist + comment "ungrouped, verified
harmless because never evaluated at a signal bar."

Codex — AGREE to session-group for uniformity (zero data change), or prefer the
documented-allowlist approach? Either is defensible; I lean group-for-uniformity.

## S2 — zero-volume RTH bar crashes the trade path (latent robustness; cannot fire on current data)

`session_vwap` (vwap.py:65) raises "volume must be positive". The trade path
(indicators.py:50) passes the full RTH frame, so one zero-volume RTH bar would
crash the whole run. The research path (research_indicators.py:97-105) deliberately
filters zero-volume rows first — so the two VWAP call sites disagree on whether a
zero-volume bar is fatal. I verified there are ZERO zero/negative-volume RTH bars
in the entire source file, so this cannot trigger on current data; it is purely a
latent asymmetry.

Proposed fix (option A, preferred): in indicators.py, compute SessionVWAP only on
positive-volume rows, mirroring research_indicators (a zero-volume bar then gets
NaN VWAP → NaN target → `_open_trade` already returns None, so no trade on that
bar — clean and consistent). Option B: relax `session_vwap` to treat zero-volume
rows as no-ops (they contribute 0/0 to the cumulative sums anyway) — but that
changes shared-math semantics. Option C: document-only (it can't fire today).

Codex — AGREE with option A (align the trade path to the research path), or prefer
B or C? I lean A: it removes the asymmetry at the call site without touching shared
math.

## S3 — ADX Wilder seed uses window-1 values (context-only, largely cancels)

`_wilder_smooth` (trend.py:143-149) nulls index 0 then seeds with the mean of the
remaining window-1 values at position window-1, vs canonical Wilder's `window`
values. Since DI = smoothed_DM / smoothed_TR, the seeding convention largely
cancels in the ratio. ADX is research-only and now session-scoped.

Proposed fix: document the window-1 seed as intentional in the `_wilder_smooth` /
`adx` docstring (bar 0 has no prior bar for TR/DM, so it is legitimately excluded).
Do NOT change the seed: a canonical change would alter the hand-calculated
reference test (`test_adx_matches_wilder_seed_reference_values`) for a difference
that cancels in DI and is invisible in the headline.

Codex — AGREE to document-only, or do you want canonical Wilder seeding (and to
update the reference test)?

## S4 — session_progress mishandles overnight sessions (unused; latent trap)

`session_progress` (time_context.py:31-33): if close_time < open_time,
`session_duration` goes negative and `in_session` is wrong. Unused by this RTH
strategy.

Proposed fix: add a fail-loud guard — raise ValueError if close_time <= open_time —
so a future overnight caller gets an explicit error instead of silently wrong
values. (Full wraparound handling can come when an overnight strategy actually
